         b'csc-textpic-text"><div class="csc-textpicHeader csc-textpicHeader-26'
         b'"><h1 class="csc-firstHeader">Mohamed Ahmed</h1></div><p class="body'
         b'text"><b>[<a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/m.ahmed/" title="Op'
         b'ens external link in new window" target="_blank" class="external-lin'
         b'k-new-window">Home Page</a>] Research:</b><br /><b>Supervisor:</b> <'
         b'a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/s.hailes" title="Opens externa'
         b'l link in new window" target="_blank" class="external-link-new-windo'
         b'w">Stephen Hailes</a> and <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/p.k'
         b'irstein/" title="Opens external link in new window" target="_blank" '
         b'class="external-link-new-window">Peter Kirstein</a>\r</p>\n<p clas'
         b's="bodytext">I\'m a completing Ph.D. student and a research fello'
         b'w at the Department of Computer Science, UCL. I am working within th'
         b'e MARS project alongside Rae Harbird and Alexandr Seleznyov. The pro'
         b'ject is based at UCL@Adastral with the at BTexact  Future technologi'
         b'es group. My academic advisors are Stephen Hailes and Peter T. Kirst'
         b'ein, and Robert Ghanea-Hercock is my industrial advisor.&nbsp;My int'
         b'erests are varied and include: component based system and frameworks'
         b', context management and adaptation for mobile systems, multi agent '
         b'systems, peer-to-peer frameworks for distributed and open systems, p'
         b'olicy representation, reasoning, management and languages, trust and'
         b' reputation management for cooperative systems, risk identification '
         b'and reasoning for security, social network definitions and applicati'
         b'on for cooperative and mobile systems.</p></div></div></div><div id='
         b'"c1202" class="csc-default"><div class="csc-textpic csc-textpic-inte'
         b'xt-left-nowrap csc-textpic-intext-left-nowrap-160"><div class="csc-t'
         b'extpic-imagewrap"><div class="csc-textpic-image csc-textpic-last"><i'
         b'mg src="fileadmin/_processed_/csm_lucia_ee4d99eecb.jpg" width="150" '
         b'height="113" alt="" border="0" /></div></div><div class="csc-textpic'
         b'-text"><div class="csc-textpicHeader csc-textpicHeader-26"><h1>Lucia'
         b' Del Prete</h1></div><p class="bodytext"><b>Research: </b>Service Co'
         b'mposition in Mobile Environments<br /><b>Supervisor</b>:&nbsp;<a hre'
         b'f="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/l.capra" title="Opens external link'
         b' in new window" target="_blank" class="external-link-new-window">Lic'
         b'ia Capra</a>\r</p>\n<p class="bodytext">In the last years two majo'
         b'r trends have emerged: a great penetration and evolution of mobile d'
         b'evices and the proliferation of blogs and personal content spaces, r'
         b'evealing a transformation of users from traditional consumers to act'
         b'ive producers of content. It will not be long before these two trend'
         b's will converge, and we will consume - in additions to the tradition'
         b'al services delivered by powerful server machines accessible via wid'
         b'e area networks and aiming to Five 9s availability - services provid'
         b'ed by devices in the surroundings that will need to be composed to d'
         b'eliver valuable functionalities to the end user.&nbsp; \r</p>\n<p '
         b'class="bodytext">In order to be successful, composite services in mo'
         b'bile environments will have to be perceived by the end user as if de'
         b'livered&nbsp; by a unique provider, reachable and available for the '
         b'duration of the service. To do so it would be required that just ser'
         b'vice compositions that can be successfully completed would be initia'
         b'ted. With this goal in mind, in my research I study how information '
         b"about users' historical mobility patterns, together with composition"
         b' semantics, can be used to maximise the chances of successfully cons'
         b'ume compound services in mobile environments. Now, selecting provide'
         b'rs based on their predicted colocation will not protect users agains'
         b't malicious ones, nor will enable them to discover services of inter'
         b'est to them. As such, I am&nbsp; now studying the integration of dis'
         b'tributed trust models and recommender systems&nbsp; to dynamically r'
         b'eason about the trustworthiness of a composition and the likeness th'
         b'at an user may find it interesting or useful.<br /><b></b></p></div>'
         b'</div></div><div id="c1247" class="csc-default"><div class="csc-text'
         b'pic csc-textpic-intext-left-nowrap csc-textpic-intext-left-nowrap-16'
         b'0"><div class="csc-textpic-imagewrap"><div class="csc-textpic-image '
         b'csc-textpic-last"><img src="fileadmin/_processed_/csm_ettore_443aeca'
         b'a93.jpg" width="150" height="176" alt="" border="0" /></div></div><d'
         b'iv class="csc-textpic-text"><div class="csc-textpicHeader csc-textpi'
         b'cHeader-26"><h1>Ettore Ferranti</h1></div><p class="bodytext"><b>[<a'
         b' href="http://web.comlab.ox.ac.uk/people/Ettore.Ferranti/" title="Op'
         b'ens external link in new window" target="_blank" class="external-lin'
         b'k-new-window">Home Page</a>] Research: Sensor Networks and Mobile Ro'
         b'bots</b><br /><b>Supervisor:</b> <a href="http://www.comlab.ox.ac.uk'
         b'/niki.trigoni/" title="Opens external link in new window" target="_b'
         b'lank" class="external-link-new-window">Niki Trigoni</a>, New College'
         b', University of Oxford \r</p>\n<p class="bodytext">Recent advances'
         b' in micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS) are allowing  the deploym'
         b'ent of small mobile nodes with sensing capabilities within an area f'
         b'or  monitoring purposes. These nodes have processing and storage cap'
         b'abilities, and are able to  communicate with each other through wire'
         b'less multi-hop links. They have the potential of sensing the  ambien'
         b't environment, and collaborating with each other to detect high-leve'
         b'l events of interest. My research is focusing on sensor network and '
         b'mobile robots deployment  in an emergency sce- <br />nario, which pr'
         b'esent critical requirements for reliable and real-time  event detect'
         b'ion. The objective is to explore a dangerous area after a disaster a'
         b'nd gather  information about hazards and victims, and to guide first'
         b' responders to the latter avoiding the former. The main challenges t'
         b'hat will be addressed are i) to provide reliable  detection of user-'
         b'defined composite events, even in the presence of intermittent failu'
         b'res in the  communication infrastructure and ii) to ensure immediate'
         b' (real-time) reaction to high-level  events by activating nearby sen'
         b'sors, communicating high-level events to interested parties, or rais'
         b'ing  alarms. At the implementation level, this project will involve '
         b'evaluating distributed event  detection techniques using simulation '
         b'tools and a real sensor network platform. </p></div></div></div><div'
         b' id="c1204" class="csc-default"><div class="csc-textpic csc-textpic-'
         b'intext-left-nowrap csc-textpic-intext-left-nowrap-160"><div class="c'
         b'sc-textpic-imagewrap"><div class="csc-textpic-image csc-textpic-last'
         b'"><img src="fileadmin/_processed_/csm_UCL-logo_3c16703a75.jpg" width'
         b'="150" height="164" alt="" border="0" /></div></div><div class="csc-'
         b'textpic-text"><div class="csc-textpicHeader csc-textpicHeader-26"><h'
         b'1>Adam Greenhalgh</h1></div><p class="bodytext"><b>[<a href="http://'
         b'www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/A.Greenhalgh/" title="Opens external link in '
         b'new window" target="_blank" class="external-link-new-window">Home Pa'
         b'ge</a>] Research: Power Conservation in Ad Hoc Networks</b><br /><b>'
         b'Supervisor:</b> <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/s.hailes" tit'
         b'le="Opens external link in new window" target="_blank" class="extern'
         b'al-link-new-window">Stephen Hailes</a>\r</p>\n<p class="bodytext">'
         b'My research interests lie in the area of mobile networking particula'
         b'rly using routing in Ad Hoc networks to conserve power in low power '
         b'radio systems. My PhD research is funded by the EPSRC through an Ind'
         b'ustrial Case with Philips Research Labs; I also have interests in In'
         b'ternet Routing and have contributed to the development of the BGP co'
         b'mponent of the <a href="http://www.xorp.org" target="_blank">XORP Ex'
         b'tensible Open Router</a> Platform during an internship at <a href="h'
         b'ttp://www.icir.org" target="_blank">ICIR</a>. </p></div></div></div>'
         b'<div id="c1205" class="csc-default"><div class="csc-textpic csc-text'
         b'pic-intext-left-nowrap csc-textpic-intext-left-nowrap-160"><div clas'
         b's="csc-textpic-imagewrap"><div class="csc-textpic-image csc-textpic-'
         b'last"><img src="fileadmin/_processed_/csm_tom_d1e249fd06.jpg" width='
         b'"150" height="121" alt="" border="0" /></div></div><div class="csc-t'
         b'extpic-text"><div class="csc-textpicHeader csc-textpicHeader-26"><h1'
         b'>Tom Hewer</h1></div><p class="bodytext"><b>[<a href="http://www.cs.'
         b'ucl.ac.uk/staff/t.hewer/" title="Opens external link in new window" '
         b'target="_blank" class="external-link-new-window">Home Page</a>] Rese'
         b'arch:</b> Large Scale and High Fidelity Vehicular Network Simulation'
         b'<br /><b>Supervisor:</b> <a href="http://ccs.chem.ucl.ac.uk/people/p'
         b'eter/index.shtml" title="Opens external link in new window" target="'
         b'_blank" class="external-link-new-window">Peter V. Coveney</a> and <a'
         b' href="http://nekovee.info/" title="Opens external link in new windo'
         b'w" target="_blank" class="external-link-new-window">Maziar Nekovee</'
         b'a>\r</p>\n<p class="bodytext">Vehicular communications technology '
         b'has been supported by the reduction in price of equipment and the in'
         b'creased availability of frequency spectrum allocation. The use of co'
         b'mputer equipment in vehicles has been well established and now the m'
         b'anufacturers are investigating ways to transmit vehicle information,'
         b' for various applications. The expense and size of vehicles means th'
         b'at testing new protocols and systems is unfeasible in the real world'
         b'. This leads to a requirement for high-&#64257;delity, timely and ac'
         b'curate computer simulation platform. Current simulation tools have b'
         b'een designed to simulate static,&nbsp; wired telecommunications netw'
         b'orks, and as wireless communication and mobility has increased, thes'
         b'e tools have become less effective. The size of vehicular traffic ne'
         b'tworks and the complexity of the mobility patterns requires a large '
         b'amount of computing power to run simulations in a timely fashion. I '
         b'will research the use of parallel and distributed grid computing sys'
         b'tems to accelerate the running time of simulation, that will operate'
         b' at large-scales and in time for decision-making and safety applicat'
         b'ions. This will enable the development and validation of vehicular n'
         b'etwork protocols and network mechanisms and perform QoS measurement '
         b'for media and data delivery systems.\r</p>\n<p class="bodytext">&n'
         b'bsp;</p>\n<p class="bodytext">&nbsp;</p></div></div></div><div id'
         b'="c1206" class="csc-default"><div class="csc-textpic csc-textpic-int'
         b'ext-left-nowrap csc-textpic-intext-left-nowrap-160"><div class="csc-'
         b'textpic-imagewrap"><div class="csc-textpic-image csc-textpic-last"><'
         b'img src="fileadmin/_processed_/csm_rae_5997b83198.jpg" width="150" h'
         b'eight="151" alt="" border="0" /></div></div><div class="csc-textpic-'
         b'text"><div class="csc-textpicHeader csc-textpicHeader-26"><h1>Rae Ha'
         b'rbird</h1></div><p class="bodytext"><b></b>\r</p>\n<p class="bodyt'
         b'ext"><b>[</b><a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/r.harbird" title'
         b'="Opens external link in new window" target="_blank" class="external'
         b'-link-new-window"><b>Home Page</b></a><b>] Research:&nbsp;</b>Adapti'
         b've resource discovery for ubiquitous computing&nbsp;<br /><b>Supervi'
         b'sor:</b> <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/s.hailes" title="Ope'
         b'ns external link in new window" target="_blank" class="external-link'
         b'-new-window">Stephen Hailes</a>\r</p>\n<p class="bodytext">I am in'
         b'vestigating the application of ad hoc routing algorithms to service '
         b'discovery and I have designed and developed RUBI, a Resource discove'
         b'ry algorithm for UBIquitous computing. RUBI is unique because it is '
         b'adaptive, altering the discovery mechanisms used based on the percei'
         b'ved stability of the network. <br /><br />Research Keywords: ubiquit'
         b'ous computing, pervasive computing, service discovery, ad hoc networ'
         b'ks, wireless routing<br /><br />Selection of Papers: <br /><br />(<a'
         b' href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/r.harbird/publications/MPAC21-h'
         b'arbird.pdf" title="Opens external link in new window" target="_blank'
         b'" class="external-link-new-window">pdf</a>) Rae Harbird, Stephen Hai'
         b'les, and Cecilia Mascolo. Adaptive resource discovery for ubiquitous'
         b' computing. <i>Middleware for Pervasive and Ad-hoc Computing</i>, 20'
         b'04.\r</p>\n<p class="bodytext">&nbsp;</p>\n<p class="bodytext">&nbs'
         b'p;</p></div></div></div><div id="c1207" class="csc-default"><div cla'
         b'ss="csc-textpic csc-textpic-intext-left-nowrap csc-textpic-intext-le'
         b'ft-nowrap-160"><div class="csc-textpic-imagewrap"><div class="csc-te'
         b'xtpic-image csc-textpic-last"><img src="fileadmin/_processed_/csm_ne'
         b'al_1a6b81a4f3.jpg" width="150" height="213" alt="" border="0" /></di'
         b'v></div><div class="csc-textpic-text"><div class="csc-textpicHeader '
         b'csc-textpicHeader-26"><h1>Neal Lathia</h1></div><p class="bodytext">'
         b'<a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/n.lathia" title="Opens extern'
         b'al link in new window" target="_blank" class="external-link-new-wind'
         b'ow"><b>[Home Page]</b></a> <b>Research</b>: Trust-Based Recommender '
         b'Systems<br /><b>Supervisors</b>: <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/st'
         b'aff/s.hailes" title="Opens external link in new window" target="_bla'
         b'nk" class="external-link-new-window">Stephen Hailes</a> and  <a href'
         b'="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/l.capra" title="Opens external link '
         b'in new window" target="_blank" class="external-link-new-window">Lici'
         b'a Capra</a><br /><br />Recommender systems are becoming ubiquitous: '
         b'they already have a dominating presence on the web, and collaborativ'
         b'e filtering is the prime example of harvesting the wisdom of the cro'
         b'wds. However, the methods used to generate recommendations often do '
         b'not take into account the temporal aspect of the process, and simply'
         b' iteratively apply one of the many classifiers available for this pr'
         b'oblem. My research addresses this gap, by focusing on modelling a re'
         b'commender system as an evolving community of interacting users who n'
         b'eed to decide who to trust.</p></div></div></div><div id="c1215" cla'
         b'ss="csc-default"><div class="csc-textpic csc-textpic-intext-left-now'
         b'rap csc-textpic-intext-left-nowrap-160"><div class="csc-textpic-imag'
         b'ewrap"><div class="csc-textpic-image csc-textpic-last"><img src="fil'
         b'eadmin/_processed_/csm_afra_f369d9a3a0.jpg" width="150" height="224"'
         b' alt="" border="0" /></div></div><div class="csc-textpic-text"><div '
         b'class="csc-textpicHeader csc-textpicHeader-26"><h1>Afra J. Mashhadi<'
         b'/h1></div><p class="bodytext"><b>[<a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/s'
         b'taff/A.JahanbakhshMashhadi/Afra_Mashhadi/About_Me.html" title="Opens'
         b' external link in new window" target="_blank" class="external-link-n'
         b'ew-window">Home Page</a>] Research:</b> Coping with unwanted content'
         b' in mobile ad hoc network <br /><b>Supervisor</b>: <a href="http://w'
         b'ww.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/l.capra" title="Opens external link in new win'
         b'dow" target="_blank" class="external-link-new-window">Licia Capra </'
         b'a><br /> <br />Web 2.0 has transformed Internet users from passive c'
         b'onsumers to active producers of digital content(e.g., personal stori'
         b'es, music, pictures, etc.). Such content can be created and shared w'
         b'orldwide at virtually no cost, by means of social networking sites. '
         b"As research on popular Web2.0 websites demonstrates, users' interest"
         b' is distributed in such a way that a tiny portion of content is of i'
         b'nterest to many users, and the vast majority of content is of intere'
         b'st to only small groups of users instead. We anticipate that the sam'
         b'e trend will move to the mobile ad hoc networks where users carry re'
         b'source constrained portable devices. My research is focused on how t'
         b'o disseminate content in MANeT, so that it reaches the interested us'
         b'ers while not overwhelming others with unwanted content. </p></div><'
         b'/div></div><div id="c1210" class="csc-default"><div class="csc-textp'
         b'ic csc-textpic-intext-left-nowrap csc-textpic-intext-left-nowrap-160'
         b'"><div class="csc-textpic-imagewrap"><div class="csc-textpic-image c'
         b'sc-textpic-last"><img src="fileadmin/_processed_/csm_UCL-logo_3c1670'
         b'3a75.jpg" width="150" height="164" alt="" border="0" /></div></div><'
         b'div class="csc-textpic-text"><div class="csc-textpicHeader csc-textp'
         b'icHeader-26"><h1>Liam McNamara</h1></div><p class="bodytext"><b>[<a '
         b'href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/l.mcnamara" title="Opens externa'
         b'l link in new window" target="_blank" class="external-link-new-windo'
         b'w">Home Page</a>] Research: </b>Content Distribution in Urban Transp'
         b'ort<br /><b>Supervisors:</b> <a href="http://www.cl.cam.ac.uk/~cm542'
         b'/" title="Opens external link in new window" target="_blank" class="'
         b'external-link-new-window">Cecilia Mascolo</a> and <a href="http://ww'
         b'w.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/l.capra" title="Opens external link in new wind'
         b'ow" target="_blank" class="external-link-new-window">Licia Capra</a>'
         b'\r</p>\n<p class="bodytext">Most people carry wireless electronic '
         b'devices, including when travelling  upon public transport. These dev'
         b'ices can play media and wirelessly procure content from neighbouring'
         b' peers. This can be a laborious, manual process for the user. To imp'
         b'rove these  systems, I use techniques for wireless connection patter'
         b'n prediction,  involving social network concepts. Incorporating an a'
         b'wareness of urban  environments, unreliable networks, malicious user'
         b's and leveraging trust  systems. To test these mechanisms I have dev'
         b'eloped software for mobile  device testbeds and exploratory network '
         b'simulations. </p></div></div></div><div id="c1211" class="csc-defaul'
         b't"><div class="csc-textpic csc-textpic-intext-left-nowrap csc-textpi'
         b'c-intext-left-nowrap-160"><div class="csc-textpic-imagewrap"><div cl'
         b'ass="csc-textpic-image csc-textpic-last"><img src="fileadmin/_proces'
         b'sed_/csm_daniele_725551accf.jpg" width="150" height="116" alt="" bor'
         b'der="0" /></div></div><div class="csc-textpic-text"><div class="csc-'
         b'textpicHeader csc-textpicHeader-26"><h1>Daniele Quercia</h1></div><p'
         b' class="bodytext"><b>[<a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/d.querc'
         b'ia" title="Opens external link in new window" target="_blank" class='
         b'"external-link-new-window">Home Page</a>] Research: </b>Trust Models'
         b' for Mobile Content-Sharing Applications <br /><b>Supervisors:</b> <'
         b'a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/s.hailes" title="Opens externa'
         b'l link in new window" target="_blank" class="external-link-new-windo'
         b'w">Stephen Hailes</a> and <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/l.c'
         b'apra" title="Opens external link in new window" target="_blank" clas'
         b's="external-link-new-window">Licia Capra <br /></a> <br />Daniele is'
         b" currently based in London where&nbsp; he's trying to create some  <"
         b'a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/d.quercia/description.pdf" tit'
         b'le="Opens external link in new window" target="_blank" class="extern'
         b'al-link-new-window">algorithmic weirdness</a> as part of his PhD at '
         b'UCL.&nbsp; He writes about mobile  2.0 research and industry on the '
         b'<a href="http://mobblog.cs.ucl.ac.uk/" target="_blank">group\'s b'
         b'log</a>. He also  speaks at top-tier conferences (such as ICDM and U'
         b'bicomp) about the way  co-located mobile users will share digital co'
         b'ntent (e.g., pictures,  videos) in the future. He is&nbsp; a <a href'
         b'="http://research.microsoft.com/aboutmsr/jobs/fellowships/scholars_e'
         b'urope_2005.aspx" title="Opens external link in new window" target="_'
         b'blank" class="external-link-new-window">Microsoft  Research Cambridg'
         b'e PhD Scholar</a> and MBA Technology Fellow&nbsp; of London  Busines'
         b's School. He worked at the National Research Council in Barcelona  a'
         b'nd at the National Institute of Informatics in Tokyo. He studied at '
         b' Politecnico di Torino for his MS in Computer Engineering and, while'
         b'  doing so, he also graduated from Universitaet Karlsruhe (Germany) '
         b'and  from University of Illinois (USA). <br /> <br />Research Keywor'
         b'ds: ubiquitous computing, pervasive computing, social  networks, sec'
         b'urity, machine learning, reputation systems <br /> <br />Selection o'
         b'f Papers: <br /> <br />(<a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/d.que'
         b'rcia/publications/quercia08mobirate.pdf" title="Opens external link '
         b'in new window" target="_blank" class="external-link-new-window">pdf<'
         b'/a>) MobiRate: Making Mobile Raters Stick to their Word. Ubicomp 200'
         b'8. <br />(<a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/d.quercia/publicati'
         b'ons/quercia07lightweight.pdf" title="Opens external link in new wind'
         b'ow" target="_blank" class="external-link-new-window">pdf</a>) Lightw'
         b'eight Distributed Trust Propagation. ICDM 2007. </p></div></div></di'
         b'v><div id="c1212" class="csc-default"><div class="csc-textpic csc-te'
         b'xtpic-intext-left-nowrap csc-textpic-intext-left-nowrap-160"><div cl'
         b'ass="csc-textpic-imagewrap"><div class="csc-textpic-image csc-textpi'
         b'c-last"><img src="fileadmin/_processed_/csm_elisa_1b64c6423c.jpg" wi'
         b'dth="150" height="200" alt="" border="0" /></div></div><div class="c'
         b'sc-textpic-text"><div class="csc-textpicHeader csc-textpicHeader-26"'
         b'><h1>Elisa Rondini</h1></div><p class="bodytext"><b>[<a href="http:/'
         b'/web4.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/E.Rondini/Elisa%20Rondini/Home.html" title='
         b'"Opens external link in new window" target="_blank" class="external-'
         b'link-new-window">Home Page</a>] Research:</b> Collaborative Computat'
         b'ion with Bandwidth Control in Wireless Sensor Networks (WSNs)<br /><'
         b'b>Supervisors:</b> <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/s.hailes" '
         b'title="Opens external link in new window" target="_blank" class="ext'
         b'ernal-link-new-window">Stephen Hailes</a> and <a href="http://www.cs'
         b'.ucl.ac.uk/staff/w.emmerich" title="Opens external link in new windo'
         b'w" target="_blank" class="external-link-new-window">Wolfgang Emmeric'
         b'h</a>\r</p>\n<p class="bodytext">In Wireless Sensor Networks (WSNs'
         b'), the tradeoff for nodes between cost, size, and battery lifetime v'
         b'ersus computational power may leave individual nodes unable by thems'
         b'elves to perform all the conceivable calculations that might be requ'
         b'ested over their lifetime. Techniques for load sharing in traditiona'
         b'l computer systems, notably computational Grid Computing systems, ha'
         b've been extensively studied but have not yet been applied in these s'
         b'ituations. Moreover, whenever nodes need to collaborate with each ot'
         b'her to achieve a global goal, they need to coordinate by exchanging '
         b'messages while distributing computation in the system. However, reso'
         b'urce-constrained devices have a limited amount of bandwidth availabi'
         b'lity. In addition, wireless communication is prone to network interf'
         b'erence and collision. Consequently, in this research, we explore the'
         b' convergence of the field of ad hoc sensor networking with that of c'
         b'omputational grids, and present novel paradigms able to take into ac'
         b'count both the computational capabilities of nodes and their local n'
         b'etwork conditions while distributing jobs computation within the sys'
         b'tem. </p></div></div></div><div id="c1213" class="csc-default"><div '
         b'class="csc-textpic csc-textpic-intext-left-nowrap csc-textpic-intext'
         b'-left-nowrap-160"><div class="csc-textpic-imagewrap"><div class="csc'
         b'-textpic-image csc-textpic-last"><img src="fileadmin/_processed_/csm'
         b'_vale_ea8752dd8a.jpg" width="150" height="210" alt="" border="0" /><'
         b'/div></div><div class="csc-textpic-text"><div class="csc-textpicHead'
         b'er csc-textpicHeader-26"><h1>Valentina Zanardi</h1></div><p class="b'
         b'odytext"><b>[<a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/v.zanardi" title'
         b'="Opens external link in new window" target="_blank" class="external'
         b'-link-new-window">Home Page</a>] Research</b>: Uncovering Relevant C'
         b'ontent Using Tag-based Recommender Systems<br /><b>Supervisor</b>: <'
         b'a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/l.capra" title="Opens external'
         b' link in new window" target="_blank" class="external-link-new-window'
         b'">Licia Capra</a><br /><br />Our work aims at solving the problem of'
         b' information retrieval for Web 2.0 scenarios in which disseminated d'
         b'ata are completely unstructured and often lack of any kind of catego'
         b'rization. Since no well-defined data model is adopted and explicit r'
         b"atings are not available to understand users' preferences, we propos"
         b'e a new information retrieval technique capable of leveraging the kn'
         b'owledge of the social network underlying collaborative tagging syste'
         b'ms.</p></div></div></div><div id="c1276" class="csc-default"><div cl'
         b'ass="csc-header csc-header-n13"><h1>Missing</h1></div><ul class="csc'
